04311nam a22005055i 9780773561427DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19881988xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735614277 a10.1515/97807735614272doi  a(DE-B1597)657089  a(OCoLC)1394872440  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aBT97.2 ǂb L279 1988eb 7aPHI0000002bisacsh04a231.7/31 aLarmer, Robert A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWater into Wine? :bAn Investigation of the Concept of Miracle /cRobert A. Larmer. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1988] 4c©1988  a1 online resource (168 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tThe Task of Definition -- tMiracles and the Laws of Nature -- tDavid Hume and Prior Probability -- tRyerson, Ross, and the Concept of Voluntary Assimilation -- tPhysicalism and the Conservation of Energy -- tWorld-Views and Falsification -- tMiracles and Evidence -- tMiracles and Apologetics -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe first is that a miracle, understood as an event produced by a transcendent agent overriding the usual course of nature, involves a violation of the laws of nature. Larmer argues that events are explained by reference to both relevant laws and units of mass/energy in the sequences to be explained. He contends that a miracle need not be conceived as involving a violation of natural law, but rather as the creation or annihilation of mass/energy by a transcendent agent. In reply to the objection that this account would violate the first law of thermo-dynamics, he distinguishes two forms of the principle -- one metaphysical, one scientific -- and aruges that a miracle would not violate the principle considered as a scientific law. The second assumption is that miracle testimony cannot serve as evidence for theism. Larmer demonstrates that the logical ties connecting the concept of miracle to theism need not imply that one must be a theist to evaluate miracle testimony properly. All that is required is that one is prepared to entertain theism as a hypothesis. Attacking these assumptions allows Larmer to show that Humean balance-of-probabilities arguments, based on a presumed conflict between evidence which establishes belief in the laws of nature and evidence in favour of miracles, miss the point if miracles need not be defined as violations of the laws of nature. He argues that, in the absence of a general argument demonstrating that the testimonial evidence in favour of miracles conflicts with the evidence for the laws of nature, it is up to the atheist to demonstrate, on a case-by-case basis, why the testimonial evidence is to be rejected. His conclusion is that, contrary to what is usually thought, the burden of proof lies not upon the shoulders of the theist, but upon the shoulders of the atheist.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356142740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773561427423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773561427/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles